Hero Honda, Jindal Steel, Oil India: India Stocks Preview

-- B y   S i d d h a r t h   P h i l i p   a n d   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-06-10T03:27:12Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-10/bharat-petroleum-hero-honda-tata-motors-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, lost
9.39 points, or 0.1 percent, to 18,384.90. The S&P CNX Nifty
Index on the National Stock Exchange slid 0.1 percent to
5,521.05. The BSE 200 Index fell 0.1 percent to 2,286.42. SGX
S&P CNX Nifty Index futures for June delivery lost 0.1 percent
to 5,514.5 as of 11:16 a.m. in  Singapore .  Bharat Petroleum Corp. (BPCL IN): India’s second-biggest
state refiner is offering 54,000 metric tons of naphtha for
loading from Mumbai and Kochi in the second half of June, said
two traders, who declined to be identified because they aren’t
authorized to speak to the media. The shares fell 1.9 percent to
612.95 rupees.  Hero Honda Motors Ltd. (HH)  : A strike by workers at a
factory of  Maruti Suzuki India Ltd. (MSIL)   may spread to
other companies such as  Hero Honda  Motors Ltd., Honda Motorcycle
& Scooter India Pvt. and Rico Auto Industries Ltd., the Press
Trust of India reported, citing Harjeet Grover, district
secretary at the All India Trade Union Congress. Hero Honda
shares lost 1.3 percent to 1,741.8 rupees. Maruti fell 0.7
percent to 1,215.05 rupees.  Indian Overseas Bank (IOB)  : The lender plans to more
than double the number of foreign offices over the next three to
four years. It intends to add 14 branches and representative
offices to its existing 10 overseas centers, with half of the
additions in  Africa , Chairman M. Narendra said in an interview
in Singapore today. Shares lost 0.8 percent to 143.15 rupees.  Jindal Steel & Power Ltd. (JSP)  : A coal washery unit of
the nation’s second-biggest producer of the alloy by value in
India’s Chhattisgarh state is under review by the Environment
Ministry, the Economic Times newspaper reported, without saying
from where it got the information. The stock added 0.2 percent
to 632.55 rupees.  Oil India Ltd. (OINL)  : The state-run explorer, planning
to spend 45 billion rupees buying companies abroad, intends to
buy a technology company that can provide services including
deep-sea well completion, Mint reported, citing a company
executive it didn’t identify. The report didn’t name any
companies Oil India may target. The stock lost 0.9 percent to
1,264.8 rupees.  Reliance Industries Ltd. (RIL)  : Fuel exports by India’s
largest publicly traded company climbed at least 15 percent in
May as the owner of the world’s biggest refining complex more
than tripled jet-fuel shipments.  The company, controlled by billionaire  Mukesh Ambani ,
shipped at least 2.3 million metric tons of oil-products from
its Jamnagar facility in western India last month, up from 2
million tons in April, according to ship-tracking data compiled
by Bloomberg and vessel fixtures from Clarkson Research Services
Ltd. The stock advanced 0.5 percent to 954 rupees.  Sundaram Finance Ltd. (SUF)  : The financial services
company may resume talks aimed at selling its general insurance
business to a  Reliance Capital Ltd. (RCAPT)   unit engaged in
the same activity, the Financial Chronicle newspaper reported,
without saying from where it got the information.  Sundaram’s board will consider a course of action based on
the terms and conditions of its license, S. Venkatesan, chief
financial officer, was cited as saying, without commenting on
the prospect of the unit’s sale. Sundaram’s shares slid 0.6
percent to 550 rupees.  To contact the reporter on this story:
